In the original box, you're looking at a Makarov pistol that shoots 9 x 18 (instead of the 9 x 19 Luger caliber 9mm).  Comes with the instruction manual, cleaning rod, pistol, and one magazine although additional magazines can be had for cheap on places like gunbroker, ebay (it's under their 10 round limit), etc.

This would be a GREAT concealed carry pistol, particularly useful for smaller/thinner framed men and very popular with females as it's accurate, easy to shoot, uses affordable ammunition, and isn't something that's going to, based on recoil, cause the user to develop a severe flinch reaction.

This particular pistol is in absolutely MINT condition, the bluing is very bright and shiny.

I have a Hogue wraparound rubber grip available for an additional $15 if you're interested.

This is the equivalent of the Bulgarians you'll see listed here from time to time.  It's superior to the Hungarian and Polish Makarovs in that the frame is steel (the Hungarian isn't) and the trigger pull is even, consistent, and doesn't require a lineman's grip strength the way the Polish versions do.

Cash sale, not interested in any trades at this time, face to face.  I live in the northwest Milwaukee 'burbs and I'm willing to drive up to 20 miles to help make this happen.   You're legally old enough and eligible to purchase a handgun in Wisconsin, I'll need a quick glance at your driver's license to confirm age if it's not obvious.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Leupold Base and Rings (Remington 700)
postcontent:
I have a Leupold one piece base for Remington 700 Long Action rifle. This one piece base is for a right handed rifle and is the most stable base you can get. It has the rear windage adjustment screws to help zero in your scope without maxing out your scopes adjustment. 

The rings are a "low" profile. The front ring is a dovetail and the rear has the windage adjustments.  They are for a 1" tube. 

This scope set up is one of the strongest and most stable systems out there. 

They idiot who had it mounted when I bought the rifle had stripped out one of the base screws so I had to have it drilled out. There is no damage to the base but it is missing a base screw. I know that most gun smiths have extras laying around and they will just grab a new one when you have the scope installed. I would recommend "The Shooting Den" for installation. 

I might consider splitting the rings from the base if you need different rings or you want the rings to put on a two piece base.  These pieces are over $40 separate. So by the time you pay tax and all that it runs you $100 just for base and rings. I'll cut that in half with no waiting.
